The selected sampling site of the respiratory tract is of great importance for interpretation of the test result. Table 1
provides an overview of available sampling techniques, with their advantages and drawbacks. Descriptions of these techniques are available elsewhere (eg, deep nasopharyngeal swabs [DNSs] and nonendoscopic bronchoalveolar lavage [nBAL],10 transtracheal aspiration [TTA]/transtracheal wash [TTW],11 and endoscopic bronchoalveolar lavage [BAL]12; Fig. 1
).
